Vietnam's National Day Observed 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, Pyongyang, August 31 (KCNA) -- The DPRK-Vietnam Friendship Association hosted a friendly meeting and film show at the Taedonggang Club for the Diplomatic Corps Tuesday on the occasion of the 60th national day of Vietnam.
 Present on invitation were Vietnamese Ambassador to the DPRK Phan Trong Thai and staff members of the embassy. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On hand were Vice-Minister of Education Jon Kuk Man who is chairman of the DPRK-Vietnam Friendship Association, officials concerned, and teachers and students of Pyongyang University of Foreign Studies. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The participants enjoyed an art performance given by students of Pyongyang Tonghung Middle School and talked about the need to boost the cooperative relations between the DPRK and Vietnam. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Prior to the meeting, they watched a Vietnamese documentary film "Vietnam 30 Years after War".

U.S. "Human Rights" Offensive under Fire in S. Korea 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, August 31 (KCNA) -- A spokesman for the Reunification Solidarity of south Korea reportedly issued a commentary on August 21 lashing at the U.S. appointment of an "envoy for the human rights issue of north Korea". The commentary charged that this appointment is a sort of attack as it goes against the spirit of the six-party talks.
 The action taken by the United States to bring forward again the "human rights issue" as part of its campaign against the north brought once again disappointment to the Koreans who desire an early settlement of the nuclear issue and touched off their anger, the commentary said, adding: The U.S., which is not entitled to talk about human rights, is persisting in its smear campaign against the north. This cannot be construed otherwise than a sinister aim to vitiate the atmosphere of national cooperation and reconciliation on the Korean Peninsula at present and bring the trend of DPRK-U.S. dialogue back to the past confrontation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 An act of blocking the reunification constitutes the worst violation of human rights on the Korean Peninsula and to cooperate in the efforts to achieve reunification and frustrate the moves for a war mean the fullest guarantee of human rights, the commentary said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It urged the U.S. to ponder over the ardent passion for reunification on the Korean Peninsula once again, withdraw the base and futile "human rights" offensive and the hostile policy toward the north and opt for warming its relations with the north at once.

Memorial Service for Victims to Explosion of Ukishima-maru 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tokyo, August 29 (KNS-KCNA) -- A memorial service was held in Maizuru City, Kyoto Prefecture, Japan, on August 24, 60 years since thousands of Koreans aboard the ship Ukishima-maru on the way back home with joy at the liberation of Korea were ruthlessly killed by the blowing up of the ship by the Japanese imperialists.
 Present there were Koreans affiliated with the General Association of Korean Residents in Japan (Chongryon) and the south Korean Residents Association in Japan and Japanese figures. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The participants first observed a silent tribute to the memory of the victims.
 Kim Tok Chun, chairman of the Santan Branch, Kyoto Prefecture, of Chongryon, in his address said those aboard the ship were Koreans who had been anxiously waiting for the day of their return home. No word and letters are adequate to describe the grievances of those people who were subjected to forcible labor and maltreatment by the Japanese imperialists, he added. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  Noting that the truth behind the blowing up of the ship has not been properly made clear over the last 60 years, he demanded the Japanese government clarify in detail the truth of the terrible incident and make an official apology and compensation to the victims and their bereaved families. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  An "evening of culture" took place on the same day.

Congratulatory Message from Fidel Castro 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, August 31 (KCNA) -- Kim Jong Il, general secretary of the Workers' Party of Korea and chairman of the National Defence Commission of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, and Kim Yong Nam, president of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, received a congratulatory message on August 29 from Fidel Castro Ruz, first secretary of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of Cuba, president of the Council of State and president of the Council of Ministers of the Republic of Cuba, on the occasion of the 45th anniversary of the opening of diplomatic ties between the two countries.
 Over the last 45 years the fraternal bonds linking the peoples, parties and governments of the two countries have been tightened and our capacity to achieve social and economic development and cope with the threat of imperialism has grown, the message said, adding: It is our will to make continued efforts to further strengthen these bonds. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The message reaffirmed firm solidarity with the Korean people in the just struggle to defend the sovereignty of the country and build a free and prosperous future and, especially, in the noble cause of the reunification of Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It wished Kim Jong Il who is leading the sagacious and brave Korean people and Kim Yong Nam new successes in their work and good health and happiness.

DPRK Young Weightlifters Prove Successful at Championships 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, August 31 (KCNA) -- DPRK boys and girls gave a good account of themselves in the 7th Asian 13-15 Group Weightlifting Championships, the 10th Asian Girls' 16-18 Group Weightlifting Championships and the 18th Asian Boys' 16-18 Group Weightlifting Championships held in Tashkent from Aug. 18 to 25.
 Korean boys and girls bagged 14 gold medals and 10 silver medals in the championships which drew weightlifters from 18 Asian countries.
 Ryang Chun Hwa and Ryu Jin Ok displayed high skills such as quick jerk and dynamic successive movement to come first in snatch, clean and jerk and total points respectively in the 44 kg category and 53 kg category of the 7th 13-15 Group championships. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Paek Un Hui carried away two gold medals in jerk and total points in the 48 category. She was awarded the technique prize of the championships. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Han Yun Gyong lifted 86kg in snatch in the 58 kg to break the record of the Asian 13-15 Group championships. She bagged a gold medal and placed second in total points.
 Meanwhile, Jin Ok Jong won the title in the snatch, clean and jerk and total points in the 48 kg category to receive three gold medals and Hong Yong Ok bagged three silver medals in snatch, clean and jerk and total points in the 69 kg category of the 10th Asian Girls' 16-18 Group Weightlifting Championships. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kim Un Dok carried away a gold medal in total points in the 62 kg category and Cha Kum Chol bagged a gold medal in snatch in the 56 kg category of the 18th Asian Boys' 16-18 Group Weightlifting Championships.

U.S. Ceaseless Aerial Espionage against DPRK
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, August 31 (KCNA) -- The U.S. imperialists committed more than 170 cases of aerial espionage against the DPRK in August by mobilizing various type strategic and tactical reconnaissance planes, according to a military source.
 U-2s made shuttle flights almost every day in the sky above the areas along the Military Demarcation Line to conduct frantic aerial photographing and electronic reconnaissance of the depth of the north. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On August 1, an overseas based E-3 spied on the military targets in the forefront area, while commanding fighters engaged in war exercises such as air-battle training, ground-target attack drill and aerial target-intercepting drill.
 A P-3 and an EP-3 made repeated flights in the air over the West and East Seas of Korea to spy on the north coastal areas and its sea-bed. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Tactical planes including RC-7Bs and RC-12s flew to spy on the areas along the front and coastal areas of the north day and night. The number of those planes involved reached 11 on Aug. 22 when the "Ulji Focus Lens-05" joint military exercises for aggression started and 12 on Aug. 23.

Famous Juvenile Aquatic Sports School
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, August 31 (KCNA) -- The Juvenile Aquatic Sports School in Pyongyang has brought up lots of reserve aquatic sportspersons including swimmers.
 Students of the school bagged most of the gold medals in the swimming and other water sports events in the 42nd National Juvenile Sports School Contest.
 Its players won more than 40 gold medals in swimming only. Some of them renewed records of the contest. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The school, founded on August 27, Juche 48 (1959), has distinguished itself in the swimming and other water sports events from the 1st National Juvenile Sports School Contest. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Over the last four decades it has gained more than 3,000 gold medals and scores of trophy cups. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The school has produced many fine sportspersons including Ju Myong Sop, Kim Kwang Il and Pae Jong Ae who won gold medals at rowing events of the 4th Asian Championships held in April, 1992. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 All these successes are associated with the unassuming efforts of teachers and couches of the school. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They have poured efforts into steadily improving the teaching contents and methods and putting training on a scientific basis to suit the world's developing aquatic sports technique. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 While paying special attention to the physical strength of the students and their basic technique, they have raised the quality of training by inventing various training equipment including hydraulic training apparatus. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They are now improving education to further develop water sports technique of the country and bring up more reserve sportspersons.

11th Reunion of Separated Koreans Ends
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mt. Kumgang resort, August 31 (KCNA) -- The 11th reunion of separated families and relatives that started at Korea's scenic Mt. Kumgang resort came to an end.
 Those from the north met their kin from the south in the wake of the reunion between those from the south and their kin from the north. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On August 29, they had group reunions with their families and relatives from the south. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Those from the north told their kin from the south about the happy life which they and all their families have led under the care of the DPRK where all people are helping and leading one another forward as one big harmonious family.
 On the same day, the Red Cross of the south side hosted a reception in honor of those from the north and those separated families and relatives from the south.
 On August 30, those from the north had family reunions with their kin from the south. They had pictures taken and exchanged souvenirs in a harmonious family atmosphere, sharing joy at their reunion. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Those from the north toured scenic Samil Lagoon with their kin from the south that day. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A ground-breaking ceremony for a reunion centre took place at Mt. Kumgang resort Wednesday. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present at the ceremony from the north side were Chairman Jang Jae On and officials of the Central Committee of the DPRK Red Cross Society and from the south side President Han Wan Sang and officials of the Red Cross of south Korea.
 The participants in the 11th reunion of separated families and relatives were on hand.
